    <h1>Chapter 2: Probability & Data Lab</h1>
    <p>Fundamentals of Probability and Statistics (25EMAB233)</p>
</header>

<div class="container">

    <h2>1. Introduction to Probability</h2>
    <p>Probability is the mathematical study of uncertainty. It allows us to predict the likelihood of future events based on sample spaces and outcomes.</p>

    <h2>2. Fundamental Rules</h2>
    <h3>Addition Rule</h3>
    <div class="formula">P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A ∩ B)</div>
    <p>Used to find the probability that <i>either</i> Event A or Event B (or both) occurs.</p>

    <h3>Bayes' Theorem</h3>
    <p>Bayes' Theorem finds the posterior probability of an event based on prior conditions.</p>
    

[Image of Bayes' theorem formula for conditional probability]

    <div class="formula">P(A|B) = [P(B|A) P(A)] / P(B)</div>

   
    
    <div class="solution">
        <b>Problem:</b> In a group, 40% are engineers. If a test is 90% accurate for engineers and 20% "false positive" for others, find the probability a person is an engineer given they passed the test.
        <br><br>
        <b>Solution using Bayes' Rule:</b><br>
        P(E) = 0.4, P(E') = 0.6<br>
        P(Pass|E) = 0.9, P(Pass|E') = 0.2<br>
        Total P(Pass) = (0.4 * 0.9) + (0.6 * 0.2) = 0.36 + 0.12 = 0.48<br>
        <b>P(E|Pass) = (0.36 / 0.48) = 0.75</b>
    </div>

    <h3>Probability Visualization</h3>
    <svg width="400" height="200" style="background:white; border:1px solid #ccc; display: block; margin: auto;">
        <circle cx="150" cy="100" r="60" fill="#3282b8" fill-opacity="0.3" stroke="#0f4c75" />
