        <text x="110" y="105">A</text>
        <text x="270" y="105">B</text>
        <text x="185" y="105" font-size="12">A ∩ B</text>
    </svg>

    <div class="lab-section">
        <h2>Lab</h2>
        <p> <b>Measures of Central Tendency</b> (Mean, Median, Mode) and <b>Dispersion</b> (Variance, Standard Deviation) along with graphical tools.</p>

        <h3>1. Lab Code </h3>
        <div class="code-block">
            <span class="comment"># Python code for Lab Tasks</span><br>
            import pandas as pd<br>
            import seaborn as sns<br>
            import matplotlib.pyplot as plt<br><br>
            
            data = [22, 25, 25, 30, 32, 35, 40, 42, 50, 100] <span class="comment"># 100 is an outlier</span><br>
            df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['Value'])<br><br>
            
            <span class="comment"># Calculating Stats</span><br>
            print("Mean:", df['Value'].mean())<br>
            print("Skewness:", df['Value'].skew())
        </div>

        <h3>2. Histogram & Skewness</h3>
        <p>Histograms represent the frequency distribution. <b>Skewness</b> indicates the asymmetry of the distribution.</p>
        
        <div class="solution">
            <b>Positive Skew:</b> Tail extends to the right (Mean > Median).<br>
            <b>Negative Skew:</b> Tail extends to the left (Mean < Median).
        </div>

        <h3>3. Boxplot & Outliers</h3>
        <p>The Boxplot is essential for identifying outliers and the interquartile range (IQR).</p>
        
        <svg width="500" height="120" style="background:white; border:1px solid #ccc; display: block; margin: auto;">
